diagnosis_prose: 'The decisive contrast was not in the row-deletion logic itself,
  but in

  how the rollouts interpreted the required output modality. The

  high-advantage rollouts (r1, r3) inspected the workbook, noticed that

  the evaluator cared about the resulting cell values in the spreadsheet,

  and produced workbook edits so that the two remaining "Chassis"

  entries appeared in the checked cells while saving the file. The

  low-advantage rollouts (r0, r2) instead wrote explanatory VBA/code text

  into the target cells A1:A15, effectively treating the task as a

  request for a code snippet to display in the sheet rather than a

  request to transform the workbook with Python/openpyxl.


  A second shared success behavior was adapting to the actual workbook

  state instead of assuming the sheet name from the user wording. The

  traces show the workbook only exposed a default sheet, so successful

  rollouts handled the real sheet that existed and still produced the

  required output file. Failed rollouts also encountered the sheet-name

  mismatch, but the dominant failure was continuing in "answer as text"

  mode after that discovery.


  In short: successful rollouts grounded on the artifact and the scoring

  target (edited workbook cells), whereas failed rollouts prioritized

  narrating or pasting a corrected macro into cells. The skill appears to

  under-anchor that, when an Excel task specifies an output workbook path

  and checked cells, the executor must perform the spreadsheet mutation

  and reserve cell writing for the requested result values, not for code

  explanations.

  '
